window.MM['oph_p2_trauma'] = [
{"q":"A factory worker presents immediately after alkali splashed into his eye. What is the FIRST step in management?","o":["Topical steroids","Cycloplegic drops","Copious irrigation","Topical antibiotics","Pressure patching"],"a":2,"e":"Immediate copious irrigation is the most important emergency step in chemical ocular injury. Treatment should begin instantly, even before detailed examination, to dilute and remove the offending chemical from the ocular surface.<br><br>Normal saline, Ringer lactate, or even clean water may be used initially. Delayed irrigation significantly worsens prognosis because alkali agents rapidly penetrate ocular tissues.<br><br>Topical steroids (A), cycloplegics (B), and antibiotics (D) are secondary measures after stabilization. Pressure patching (E) is contraindicated because retained chemicals may continue tissue damage.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which type of chemical ocular injury generally causes the most severe damage?","o":["Acid burn","Thermal burn","Alkali burn","UV radiation injury","Superficial foreign body"],"a":2,"e":"Alkali burns are more dangerous because alkaline substances penetrate ocular tissues rapidly through saponification of cell membrane lipids. This allows deep stromal and anterior segment damage within minutes.<br><br>Lime, ammonia, and caustic soda are common causes. Severe burns may damage limbal stem cells, trabecular meshwork, and lens. Alkali penetrating via lipid saponification while acid is limited by coagulation necrosis is the single most testable contrast here.<br><br>Acid burns (A) generally produce coagulation necrosis that limits deeper penetration. Thermal burns (B) are usually more localized externally. UV injury (D) primarily affects corneal epithelium.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ocular structure is most important prognostically in chemical burns?","o":["Lens","Retina","Limbal stem cells","Vitreous","Optic disc"],"a":2,"e":"Limbal stem cells are essential for regeneration of corneal epithelium. Severe chemical burns destroying limbal stem cells lead to persistent epithelial defects, conjunctivalization, and corneal vascularization.<br><br>The extent of limbal ischemia strongly predicts visual prognosis and guides classification systems such as Roper-Hall grading.<br><br>Lens (A), retina (B), vitreous (D), and optic disc (E) are less important initial prognostic indicators in surface chemical injury.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"White ischemic limbus after chemical injury indicates:","o":["Mild injury","Good prognosis","Limbal stem cell damage","Viral keratitis","Acute glaucoma"],"a":2,"e":"A white ischemic limbus indicates severe vascular compromise and destruction of limbal stem cells. This finding signifies a poor prognosis because epithelial regeneration becomes severely impaired.<br><br>The degree of limbal ischemia is a central component of chemical injury grading systems and correlates with risk of corneal scarring and vascularization. The extent of perilimbal blanching is the key prognostic indicator graded in chemical injury classifications.<br><br>Mild injuries (A) preserve limbal vasculature. Good prognosis (B) occurs when ischemia is minimal. Viral keratitis (D) and acute glaucoma (E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which chemical is classically associated with severe alkali ocular injury?","o":["Sulfuric acid","Hydrochloric acid","Ammonia","Acetic acid","Citric acid"],"a":2,"e":"Ammonia causes particularly severe alkali burns because it penetrates ocular tissues rapidly. The chemical reaches deeper anterior segment structures quickly and may produce devastating permanent damage.<br><br>Industrial and agricultural exposure are common causes. Severe burns may lead to glaucoma, cataract, and limbal stem cell deficiency.<br><br>Sulfuric acid (A) and hydrochloric acid (B) are acids rather than alkalis. Acetic acid (D) and citric acid (E) are comparatively weaker irritants.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which grade of Roper-Hall classification has the best prognosis?","o":["Grade I","Grade II","Grade III","Grade IV","Grade V"],"a":0,"e":"Grade I chemical injury in the Roper-Hall classification has an excellent prognosis because the cornea remains clear and limbal ischemia is absent.<br><br>Prompt treatment usually leads to complete recovery without visually significant complications. Prognosis worsens progressively with increasing limbal ischemia and corneal haze.<br><br>Grades II-IV (B-D) involve increasing tissue damage. Traditional Roper-Hall classification has four grades, making option E invalid.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which medication is commonly used after chemical burns to reduce ciliary spasm and pain?","o":["Pilocarpine","Atropine","Timolol","Brimonidine","Acetazolamide"],"a":1,"e":"Atropine is used after chemical injury to produce cycloplegia, relieve painful ciliary spasm, and prevent posterior synechiae formation if associated inflammation develops.<br><br>Cycloplegics improve patient comfort significantly and stabilize the blood-aqueous barrier during acute inflammation.<br><br>Pilocarpine (A) causes miosis and worsens pain. Timolol (C), brimonidine (D), and acetazolamide (E) are antiglaucoma agents.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Corneal haze obscuring iris details after chemical injury indicates:","o":["Mild injury","Excellent prognosis","Severe stromal involvement","Normal healing","Episcleritis"],"a":2,"e":"Dense corneal haze obscuring iris details indicates significant stromal damage and deeper ocular involvement. This finding correlates with severe chemical injury and poorer visual prognosis.<br><br>Severe stromal injury increases risk of scarring, vascularization, ulceration, and secondary glaucoma.<br><br>Mild injury (A) generally preserves corneal clarity. Excellent prognosis (B) occurs in superficial burns. Episcleritis (E) does not produce corneal haze.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which vitamin is commonly prescribed after severe chemical burns to promote collagen synthesis and healing?","o":["Vitamin A","Vitamin B12","Vitamin C","Vitamin D","Vitamin K"],"a":2,"e":"Vitamin C supports collagen synthesis and reduces corneal stromal ulceration after severe chemical burns. Ascorbate deficiency may contribute to corneal melting during healing.<br><br>Both topical and systemic vitamin C may be used in severe burns as part of supportive therapy.<br><br>Vitamin A (A) supports epithelial health but is less specifically linked with collagen stabilization. Vitamins B12, D, and K (B, D, E) are not primary therapies.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which complication may develop late after severe alkali burns?","o":["Retinitis pigmentosa","Cataract and glaucoma","Optic neuritis","Macular hole","Retinoblastoma"],"a":1,"e":"Severe alkali burns may damage trabecular meshwork and lens, leading to secondary glaucoma and cataract formation later. Chronic inflammation and scarring contribute further complications.<br><br>Long-term follow-up is essential because glaucoma may appear months or years after initial injury.<br><br>Retinitis pigmentosa (A), optic neuritis (C), macular hole (D), and retinoblastoma (E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which acid causes particularly severe ocular burns because of combined thermal and chemical effects?","o":["Acetic acid","Sulfuric acid","Citric acid","Boric acid","Carbonic acid"],"a":1,"e":"Sulfuric acid produces severe ocular damage because it causes both chemical coagulation necrosis and thermal injury during reaction with tissues.<br><br>Battery explosions commonly expose patients to sulfuric acid burns and require immediate irrigation.<br><br>Acetic acid (A), citric acid (C), boric acid (D), and carbonic acid (E) are comparatively less destructive.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"What is the main mechanism of tissue injury in alkali burns?","o":["Coagulation necrosis","Saponification of cell membranes","Vascular thrombosis only","Infective inflammation","Osmotic dehydration"],"a":1,"e":"Alkali burns cause saponification of fatty acids within cell membranes, allowing rapid penetration into deeper tissues and progressive destruction.<br><br>This mechanism explains why alkali burns are more severe than most acid injuries.<br><br>Coagulation necrosis (A) is more typical of acid burns. Infective inflammation (D) is secondary rather than primary.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which finding suggests a poor prognosis after ocular chemical injury?","o":["Clear cornea","Absence of limbal ischemia","Total epithelial healing","More than 50% limbal ischemia","Mild conjunctival injection"],"a":3,"e":"Extensive limbal ischemia indicates major limbal stem cell destruction and strongly predicts poor healing and corneal surface failure.<br><br>These patients are at high risk for vascularization, persistent epithelial defects, and corneal opacity.<br><br>Clear cornea (A) and absent ischemia (B) indicate better prognosis. Mild injection (E) is less severe.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Thermal ocular burns most commonly affect which structure initially?","o":["Retina","Optic nerve","Eyelids and ocular surface","Vitreous","Macula"],"a":2,"e":"Thermal burns usually affect eyelids, conjunctiva, and superficial corneal tissues because blinking reflex protects deeper structures rapidly.<br><br>Hot liquids, steam, and flames are common causes. Severe exposure may still damage cornea significantly.<br><br>Retina (A), optic nerve (B), vitreous (D), and macula (E) are generally protected from isolated thermal exposure.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which topical drug should generally be avoided in acute chemical burns because it delays epithelial healing?","o":["Lubricants","Topical anesthetics for repeated use","Cycloplegics","Antibiotics","Artificial tears"],"a":1,"e":"Repeated topical anesthetic use is toxic to corneal epithelium and delays healing significantly. Although anesthetics may assist examination initially, unsupervised prolonged use is dangerous.<br><br>Persistent abuse can produce neurotrophic keratopathy and corneal ulceration.<br><br>Lubricants (A), cycloplegics (C), antibiotics (D), and tears (E) are beneficial supportive treatments.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which grading system is classically used for ocular chemical injuries?","o":["Ishihara classification","Snellen grading","Roper-Hall classification","ETDRS grading","Foster classification"],"a":2,"e":"The Roper-Hall classification grades ocular chemical injuries based on corneal haze and extent of limbal ischemia. Prognosis worsens with increasing grade.<br><br>It remains one of the most commonly tested chemical injury classifications in ophthalmology examinations.<br><br>Ishihara (A) tests color vision. Snellen (B) measures visual acuity. ETDRS (D) relates to retinal studies.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Persistent epithelial defect after chemical injury primarily suggests deficiency of:","o":["Retina","Limbal stem cells","Lens capsule","Vitreous support","Optic nerve fibers"],"a":1,"e":"Persistent epithelial defects commonly indicate limbal stem cell deficiency because normal corneal epithelial regeneration cannot occur.<br><br>These patients may later require limbal stem cell transplantation for ocular surface reconstruction.<br><br>Retina (A), lens capsule (C), vitreous (D), and optic nerve fibers (E) are unrelated to epithelial regeneration.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which sign is typical of severe alkali injury?","o":["Minimal pain only","White opaque cornea","Isolated subconjunctival hemorrhage","Purely conjunctival itching","Papillary hypertrophy only"],"a":1,"e":"A white opaque cornea indicates severe stromal damage and edema after alkali penetration. Severe burns may obscure iris details completely.<br><br>This finding correlates with poor prognosis and high risk of permanent visual impairment.<br><br>Subconjunctival hemorrhage (C) and itching (D) are less characteristic severe findings.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which topical therapy is commonly used early after chemical injury to suppress inflammation?","o":["Steroids","Pilocarpine","Antifungals","Miotics","Hypertonic saline only"],"a":0,"e":"Topical corticosteroids reduce inflammation and leukocyte-mediated tissue destruction during the acute phase of chemical injury.<br><br>However, prolonged uncontrolled steroid use may impair collagen synthesis and increase corneal melting risk, so careful monitoring is necessary.<br><br>Pilocarpine (B) worsens ciliary spasm. Antifungals (C) are unnecessary unless infection exists. Miotics (D) are not indicated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ocular emergency requires irrigation until conjunctival sac pH normalizes?","o":["Retinal detachment","Chemical injury","Vitreous hemorrhage","Optic neuritis","Chalazion"],"a":1,"e":"Chemical ocular injury requires continuous irrigation until ocular surface pH returns to normal because residual chemical particles may continue tissue destruction.<br><br>Litmus paper or pH strips are used repeatedly to monitor normalization during emergency management.<br><br>Retinal detachment (A), vitreous hemorrhage (C), optic neuritis (D), and chalazion (E) do not require ocular irrigation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with severe alkali burn develops elevated intraocular pressure one week later. What is the most likely mechanism?","o":["Retinal detachment","Trabecular meshwork damage","Lens dislocation","Vitreous hemorrhage","Optic neuritis"],"a":1,"e":"Alkali chemicals penetrate deeply into the anterior segment and may damage the trabecular meshwork directly, impairing aqueous outflow and causing secondary glaucoma.<br><br>Inflammatory debris and scarring may worsen pressure elevation over time. Long-term monitoring of intraocular pressure is essential after severe chemical burns.<br><br>Retinal detachment (A), vitreous hemorrhage (D), and optic neuritis (E) are unrelated mechanisms. Lens dislocation (C) does not directly explain early pressure rise.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which chemical injury grading parameter most strongly predicts visual outcome?","o":["Eyelid edema","Corneal epithelial defect size only","Limbal ischemia extent","Conjunctival discharge","Pupillary size"],"a":2,"e":"The degree of limbal ischemia is the single most important prognostic factor in ocular chemical burns because limbal stem cell destruction severely impairs corneal epithelial regeneration.<br><br>Extensive ischemia correlates strongly with persistent epithelial defects, vascularization, corneal opacity, and permanent visual loss.<br><br>Eyelid edema (A) and discharge (D) are less prognostically significant. Pupillary size (E) does not determine outcome directly.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Hydrofluoric acid is particularly dangerous because it:","o":["Causes only superficial injury","Cannot penetrate the cornea","Penetrates deeply despite being an acid","Produces only conjunctivitis","Causes isolated retinal toxicity"],"a":2,"e":"Unlike most acids that produce protective coagulation necrosis, hydrofluoric acid penetrates rapidly into ocular tissues and can cause severe anterior segment destruction.<br><br>This makes hydrofluoric acid injuries clinically behave more like alkali burns with potentially devastating consequences.<br><br>Superficial injury (A) is incorrect. Isolated retinal toxicity (E) is not the primary mechanism.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"During irrigation of chemical eye injury, eversion of eyelids is important mainly to:","o":["Improve visual acuity","Detect retinal hemorrhage","Remove retained chemical particles","Assess optic nerve damage","Reduce cataract formation"],"a":2,"e":"Retained particulate chemicals trapped in the fornices may continue releasing toxic substances and worsen ocular injury even after initial irrigation.<br><br>Eyelid eversion is therefore essential during emergency management to remove hidden debris completely.<br><br>Visual acuity (A), retinal hemorrhage (B), and optic nerve damage (D) are unrelated to this maneuver directly.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which complication is especially associated with limbal stem cell deficiency after chemical burns?","o":["Conjunctivalization of cornea","Macular degeneration","Retinal tear","Optic atrophy","Vitreous prolapse"],"a":0,"e":"Limbal stem cell deficiency allows conjunctival epithelium and blood vessels to grow over the corneal surface, causing conjunctivalization and severe visual impairment.<br><br>Patients may develop recurrent epithelial defects, vascularization, and chronic ocular surface instability.<br><br>Macular degeneration (B), retinal tear (C), optic atrophy (D), and vitreous prolapse (E) are unrelated surface complications.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ocular burn commonly causes coagulation necrosis limiting deeper penetration?","o":["Alkali burn","Acid burn","Radiation burn","Thermal burn","Electrical burn"],"a":1,"e":"Acid burns denature and precipitate tissue proteins, creating coagulation necrosis that forms a protective barrier against deeper penetration.<br><br>This explains why most acid injuries are less destructive than alkali injuries, except hydrofluoric acid.<br><br>Alkali burns (A) produce liquefactive necrosis and deeper penetration. Thermal burns (D) are different mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which therapeutic membrane may be used in severe chemical burns to promote epithelial healing?","o":["Amniotic membrane graft","Retinal implant","Silicone buckle","Corneal tattoo","Scleral buckle"],"a":0,"e":"Amniotic membrane transplantation promotes epithelial healing, reduces inflammation, and decreases fibrosis after severe ocular surface burns.<br><br>It acts as a biological scaffold and is increasingly used in moderate to severe chemical injuries.<br><br>Retinal implants (B), scleral buckles (E), and silicone buckles (C) are retinal procedures unrelated to ocular surface burns.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with severe chemical injury develops corneal melting. Which pathological process is primarily responsible?","o":["Collagen degradation","Retinal ischemia","Vitreous traction","Lens swelling","Optic neuritis"],"a":0,"e":"Inflammatory enzymes such as collagenases degrade corneal stromal collagen after severe chemical injury, causing corneal melting and possible perforation.<br><br>Vitamin C and tetracyclines may help reduce stromal degradation during treatment.<br><br>Retinal ischemia (B), vitreous traction (C), and optic neuritis (E) are unrelated mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which cell population is primarily destroyed in limbal ischemia?","o":["Photoreceptors","Goblet cells only","Corneal epithelial stem cells","Retinal ganglion cells","Lens epithelial cells"],"a":2,"e":"Limbal ischemia destroys corneal epithelial stem cells responsible for continual regeneration of the corneal surface.<br><br>Loss of these cells causes persistent epithelial defects and conjunctivalization.<br><br>Photoreceptors (A), retinal ganglion cells (D), and lens epithelial cells (E) are unrelated to limbal injury.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which pH should ideally be achieved before stopping ocular irrigation?","o":["3","5","Neutral physiologic pH","10","Strongly alkaline pH"],"a":2,"e":"Irrigation should continue until conjunctival sac pH returns to physiologic neutrality because residual abnormal pH indicates ongoing chemical activity.<br><br>Repeated pH testing with litmus paper helps guide adequacy of irrigation.<br><br>Strongly acidic (A, B) or alkaline (D, E) pH values indicate incomplete neutralization.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ocular burn may occur after prolonged ultraviolet exposure from welding arcs?","o":["Retinitis pigmentosa","Photokeratitis","Macular hole","Optic atrophy","Choroiditis"],"a":1,"e":"Photokeratitis is ultraviolet-induced corneal epithelial injury commonly caused by welding arcs, snow reflection, or tanning lamps.<br><br>Patients present several hours later with severe pain, watering, photophobia, and punctate epithelial erosions.<br><br>Retinitis pigmentosa (A), macular hole (C), and optic atrophy (D) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which symptom is most characteristic of photokeratitis?","o":["Gradual painless visual loss","Leukocoria","Proptosis","Severe foreign body sensation","Floaters"],"a":3,"e":"Photokeratitis causes diffuse epithelial injury producing intense foreign body sensation, watering, photophobia, and blepharospasm.<br><br>Symptoms usually begin several hours after UV exposure because epithelial cell death is delayed.<br><br>Proptosis (C), leukocoria (B), and floaters (E) are unrelated findings.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which preventive measure is most important for industrial chemical eye injuries?","o":["Oral steroids","Routine antibiotics","Cycloplegics","Protective eyewear","Artificial tears"],"a":3,"e":"Most industrial chemical eye injuries are preventable with appropriate protective goggles and workplace safety education.<br><br>Young industrial workers represent the highest-risk population in most epidemiological studies.<br><br>Steroids (A) and antibiotics (B) are treatments rather than preventive measures.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which chemical burn finding suggests severe anterior segment ischemia?","o":["Conjunctival hyperemia","Normal corneal sensation","Mild watering","White avascular conjunctiva","Subconjunctival hemorrhage"],"a":3,"e":"A white avascular ocular surface indicates severe ischemic damage with loss of limbal and conjunctival blood supply.<br><br>Such injuries carry poor prognosis because inflammatory and reparative cells cannot reach damaged tissues effectively.<br><br>Conjunctival hyperemia (A) indicates preserved vascularity rather than ischemia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which late complication may follow severe photokeratitis repeatedly over years?","o":["Pterygium formation","Retinoblastoma","Lens dislocation","Optic glioma","Endophthalmitis"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic ultraviolet exposure contributes to pterygium formation through degenerative and inflammatory conjunctival changes.<br><br>Outdoor workers and welders have increased risk because of prolonged UV exposure.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (B), optic glioma (D), and endophthalmitis (E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which antibiotic is commonly prescribed prophylactically after chemical burns?","o":["Topical broad-spectrum antibiotic","Oral antituberculous therapy","Antiviral injections","Intravitreal antibiotics","Systemic antifungals routinely"],"a":0,"e":"Topical broad-spectrum antibiotics help prevent secondary bacterial infection after epithelial compromise caused by chemical injury.<br><br>The damaged corneal epithelium increases susceptibility to microbial keratitis during healing.<br><br>Antituberculous therapy (B), antivirals (C), and intravitreal antibiotics (D) are not routine management.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ocular tissue is most resistant to thermal burns because of blink reflex protection?","o":["Corneal epithelium","Limbus","Eyelid skin","Conjunctiva","Retina"],"a":4,"e":"The blink reflex and Bell phenomenon help protect deeper intraocular structures such as retina during thermal exposure.<br><br>Most thermal injuries therefore remain localized to eyelids and ocular surface tissues.<br><br>Corneal epithelium (A), conjunctiva (D), and eyelids (C) are commonly affected directly.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which condition may require limbal stem cell transplantation after chemical burns?","o":["Persistent limbal stem cell deficiency","Mild conjunctivitis","Chalazion","Episcleritis","Hordeolum"],"a":0,"e":"Patients with severe limbal stem cell deficiency may require limbal stem cell transplantation to restore corneal epithelial regeneration and ocular surface stability.<br><br>Without transplantation, persistent epithelial breakdown and conjunctivalization continue.<br><br>Conjunctivitis (B), chalazion (C), and episcleritis (D) do not require stem cell grafting.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which clinical sign indicates severe corneal stromal edema after chemical injury?","o":["Transparent cornea","Lid crusting","Normal iris visibility","Fine conjunctival papillae","Corneal opacity"],"a":4,"e":"Corneal opacity reflects significant stromal edema and collagen damage after severe chemical injury.<br><br>Opacity obscuring iris details signifies deeper corneal involvement and worse prognosis.<br><br>Transparent cornea (A) indicates mild injury. Papillae (D) occur in allergy.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which management principle is most critical in ocular chemical burns?","o":["Immediate treatment before detailed examination","Delaying treatment until ophthalmologist arrives","Eye patching immediately","Avoiding irrigation initially","Performing OCT first"],"a":0,"e":"Chemical ocular burns are true ophthalmic emergencies in which immediate irrigation must begin before history taking or detailed examination. Delayed treatment dramatically worsens prognosis.<br><br>Rapid dilution and removal of chemicals are the cornerstone of management and vision preservation.<br><br>Delaying treatment (B) and avoiding irrigation (D) are dangerous. OCT (E) is unnecessary initially.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A young man is struck in the eye by a cricket ball. He presents with painful visual loss and blood layering in the anterior chamber. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Hypopyon","Endophthalmitis","Vitreous hemorrhage","Corneal ulcer","Hyphema"],"a":4,"e":"Hyphema refers to blood within the anterior chamber, commonly occurring after blunt ocular trauma due to rupture of iris or ciliary body vessels. Patients present with pain, blurred vision, and photophobia.<br><br>Rebleeding is an important complication and may occur several days after injury. Intraocular pressure monitoring is essential because secondary glaucoma may develop.<br><br>Hypopyon (A) consists of inflammatory cells rather than blood. Vitreous hemorrhage (C) occurs posteriorly. Corneal ulcer (D) and endophthalmitis (B) are infective conditions.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops a teardrop-shaped pupil after penetrating ocular trauma. Which diagnosis should be suspected immediately?","o":["Acute glaucoma","Retinal detachment","Globe rupture","Corneal abrasion","Optic neuritis"],"a":2,"e":"A peaked or teardrop-shaped pupil pointing toward a wound strongly suggests globe perforation with iris prolapse. This is a classic sign of open globe injury.<br><br>The eye must be protected immediately with a rigid shield, and pressure on the globe must be avoided to prevent extrusion of intraocular contents.<br><br>Acute glaucoma (A) causes a mid-dilated pupil. Retinal detachment (B) affects the posterior segment. Corneal abrasion (D) does not distort the pupil.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most appropriate when intraocular foreign body is suspected after penetrating trauma?","o":["MRI orbit","B-scan without caution","CT scan orbit","Schirmer test","Keratometry"],"a":2,"e":"CT scan of the orbit is the investigation of choice for suspected intraocular foreign body because it accurately detects metallic and many nonmetallic foreign bodies safely.<br><br>MRI is contraindicated when metallic foreign body is possible because migration may cause further ocular damage.<br><br>Schirmer test (D) and keratometry (E) are unrelated. B-scan (B) may be contraindicated if globe rupture is open and pressure risks extrusion.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient hit by a fist develops circumferential subconjunctival hemorrhage, shallow anterior chamber, and low intraocular pressure. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Angle recession glaucoma","Episcleritis","Hyphema only","Corneal abrasion","Globe rupture"],"a":4,"e":"Circumferential subconjunctival hemorrhage with hypotony after blunt trauma strongly suggests globe rupture. A shallow anterior chamber may indicate leakage of aqueous humor through scleral or corneal rupture.<br><br>This is an ophthalmic emergency requiring urgent surgical repair and protection of the eye from further pressure.<br><br>Angle recession glaucoma (A) develops later. Corneal abrasion (D) does not usually cause hypotony or chamber shallowing.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which retinal finding is classically associated with blunt ocular trauma?","o":["Cherry red spot","Retinitis pigmentosa","Drusen","Berlin edema","Cotton wool spots only"],"a":3,"e":"Berlin edema, also called commotio retinae, is transient retinal whitening caused by blunt trauma-induced disruption of outer retinal photoreceptors. The macula is commonly affected.<br><br>Patients experience decreased vision following trauma. Most cases improve spontaneously, although severe injuries may leave permanent visual impairment.<br><br>Cherry red spot (A) occurs in central retinal artery occlusion. Drusen (C) occur in macular degeneration. Retinitis pigmentosa (B) is inherited.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which sign is most suggestive of orbital blowout fracture after blunt trauma?","o":["Increased intraocular pressure","Pterygium formation","Corneal ulceration","Iris neovascularization","Diplopia on upward gaze"],"a":4,"e":"Orbital blowout fractures commonly trap the inferior rectus muscle, producing limitation of elevation and diplopia on upward gaze. Infraorbital numbness may coexist.<br><br>CT scan of orbit is the preferred imaging investigation. Surgical repair may be needed if persistent entrapment exists.<br><br>Corneal ulceration (C), iris neovascularization (D), and pterygium (B) are unrelated findings.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient presents after penetrating trauma with severe pain, reduced vision, and purulent intraocular inflammation. Which complication is most likely?","o":["Retinitis pigmentosa","Endophthalmitis","Keratoconus","Episcleritis","Papilledema"],"a":1,"e":"Endophthalmitis is a severe intraocular infection that may occur after penetrating ocular trauma, especially with contaminated foreign bodies. Patients develop severe pain, hypopyon, and rapidly worsening vision.<br><br>Urgent intravitreal antibiotics and possible vitrectomy are often required to preserve vision.<br><br>Keratoconus (C), episcleritis (D), and papilledema (E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which anterior segment complication may occur years after blunt trauma because of trabecular meshwork damage?","o":["Angle recession glaucoma","Acute conjunctivitis","Retinal tear","Macular edema only","Episcleritis"],"a":0,"e":"Blunt trauma may split the ciliary body face and damage trabecular meshwork, producing angle recession. Secondary glaucoma can appear months or years later.<br><br>Gonioscopy is essential in traumatic glaucoma assessment because angle recession may otherwise be missed clinically.<br><br>Retinal tear (C) occurs posteriorly. Conjunctivitis (B) and episcleritis (E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with penetrating injury has prolapse of dark tissue through a corneal wound. What structure is most likely prolapsing?","o":["Retina","Choroid","Iris","Optic nerve","Vitreous only"],"a":2,"e":"Iris prolapse commonly occurs through corneal or limbal wounds in penetrating trauma because anterior chamber structures are pushed outward by intraocular pressure.<br><br>The prolapsed iris appears dark brown or black and should not be manipulated outside sterile surgical repair conditions.<br><br>Retina (A) and choroid (B) are posterior structures. Vitreous (E) appears gelatinous rather than pigmented.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is contraindicated in suspected open globe injury?","o":["Visual acuity testing","CT scan orbit","Pupillary examination","Slit-lamp examination carefully","Tonometry"],"a":4,"e":"Tonometry is contraindicated in suspected globe rupture because pressure on the eye may extrude intraocular contents and worsen injury.<br><br>Diagnosis relies on careful inspection, Seidel testing, and imaging when needed. Orbital MRI being contraindicated when a metallic intraocular foreign body is suspected is a classic safety point.<br><br>Visual acuity (A) and pupillary examination (C) remain important unless impossible safely. CT orbit (B) is useful diagnostically.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A boxer develops sudden painless loss of vision after blunt trauma. Fundoscopy reveals a pale retina with cherry red spot. Which artery is most likely occluded?","o":["Central retinal artery","Posterior ciliary artery","Ophthalmic vein","Vortex vein","Lacrimal artery"],"a":0,"e":"Blunt trauma occasionally causes central retinal artery occlusion due to vascular spasm or compression. The classic fundoscopic appearance includes diffuse retinal whitening with cherry red spot at the fovea.<br><br>Visual prognosis is generally poor unless perfusion returns rapidly.<br><br>Posterior ciliary arteries (B) mainly supply choroid. Ophthalmic vein (C) and vortex veins (D) are venous structures.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which sign is characteristic of traumatic iridodialysis?","o":["Lens opacity only","Vitreous detachment only","Corneal ulcer","Peripheral iris tear at its root","Retinal whitening only"],"a":3,"e":"Iridodialysis is separation of the iris root from the ciliary body following blunt trauma. Patients may develop monocular diplopia, glare, and D-shaped pupil deformity.<br><br>Small tears may be asymptomatic, while large defects can require surgical repair.<br><br>Lens opacity (A) suggests traumatic cataract. Retinal whitening (E) suggests commotio retinae.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops rust deposition around a retained metallic corneal foreign body. What is this ring called?","o":["Kayser-Fleischer ring","Fleischer ring","Weiss ring","Rust ring","Vossius ring"],"a":3,"e":"Iron-containing corneal foreign bodies may oxidize rapidly, creating a surrounding rust ring within corneal tissue.<br><br>Complete removal is important because retained rust causes inflammation and delayed epithelial healing. Rust ring formation around a retained iron foreign body is a hallmark sign worth committing to memory.<br><br>Kayser-Fleischer ring (A) occurs in Wilson disease. Fleischer ring (B) occurs in keratoconus. Vossius ring (E) follows blunt trauma on lens capsule.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which lens finding is classically associated with blunt ocular trauma?","o":["Vossius ring","Kayser-Fleischer ring","Argyll Robertson pupil","Bitot spots","Arcus senilis"],"a":0,"e":"A Vossius ring is a circular pigment imprint on the anterior lens capsule caused by impact of the pupillary margin against the lens during blunt trauma.<br><br>It represents traumatic iris pigment deposition and is often transient.<br><br>Kayser-Fleischer ring (B) occurs in Wilson disease. Arcus senilis (E) is peripheral corneal lipid deposition.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which retinal complication may occur after severe blunt trauma because of vitreoretinal traction?","o":["Retinal detachment","Pinguecula","Episcleritis","Keratoconus","Chalazion"],"a":0,"e":"Blunt trauma may create retinal tears through vitreoretinal traction, leading to rhegmatogenous retinal detachment. Patients complain of flashes, floaters, and curtain-like visual loss.<br><br>Peripheral retinal examination is therefore essential after significant ocular trauma.<br><br>Pinguecula (B), episcleritis (C), and chalazion (E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"What is the most appropriate immediate management for suspected open globe injury?","o":["Eye patch with pressure","Rigid eye shield and urgent referral","Tonometry immediately","Pilocarpine drops","Gonioscopy"],"a":1,"e":"Suspected globe rupture requires immediate protection with a rigid eye shield to avoid external pressure and extrusion of ocular contents.<br><br>Urgent ophthalmic surgical repair is usually required. Patients should remain fasting in anticipation of surgery.<br><br>Pressure patching (A) is contraindicated. Tonometry (C) risks worsening rupture. Gonioscopy (E) should be avoided acutely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which traumatic condition is most likely to cause relative afferent pupillary defect after blunt injury?","o":["Corneal abrasion","Optic nerve injury","Conjunctivitis","Episcleritis","Chalazion"],"a":1,"e":"Traumatic optic neuropathy may occur after blunt orbital trauma and commonly produces RAPD with decreased visual acuity and color vision defects.<br><br>CT imaging is important to evaluate associated orbital fractures and optic canal involvement.<br><br>Corneal abrasion (A) causes pain but not RAPD. Episcleritis (D) and chalazion (E) do not affect optic pathways.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A child hit by a ball develops painful photophobia and cells in the anterior chamber without globe rupture. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Traumatic iritis","Endophthalmitis","Keratoconus","Pingueculitis","Retinal dystrophy"],"a":0,"e":"Blunt trauma may produce anterior uveal inflammation known as traumatic iritis. Patients develop pain, photophobia, and anterior chamber cells several hours after injury.<br><br>Cycloplegics and topical steroids are commonly used during treatment.<br><br>Endophthalmitis (B) is infective and usually follows penetrating injury. Keratoconus (C) is degenerative ectasia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which sign suggests orbital emphysema after orbital fracture?","o":["Papilledema","Corneal vascularization","Hypopyon","Crepitus around orbit","Lens coloboma"],"a":3,"e":"Orbital emphysema occurs when air enters orbital tissues through fractures communicating with paranasal sinuses. Palpable crepitus is characteristic clinically.<br><br>Patients should avoid nose blowing because additional air may worsen orbital pressure.<br><br>Papilledema (A) and hypopyon (C) are unrelated findings.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which traumatic injury most commonly causes sympathetic ophthalmia?","o":["Blunt trauma without rupture","Penetrating ocular trauma","Episcleritis","Chemical burn only","Corneal abrasion"],"a":1,"e":"Sympathetic ophthalmia is a bilateral granulomatous panuveitis occurring after penetrating trauma or surgery exposing uveal antigens. The uninjured eye becomes inflamed immunologically.<br><br>Early recognition and systemic immunosuppression are essential to preserve vision.<br><br>Blunt trauma without rupture (A) rarely exposes uveal tissue sufficiently. Corneal abrasion (E) is superficial.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A construction worker presents after hammering metal on metal without eye protection. Vision is reduced and a small self-sealed corneal wound is noted. Which diagnosis must be excluded urgently?","o":["Episcleritis","Chalazion","Dry eye disease","Pinguecula","Intraocular foreign body"],"a":4,"e":"High-velocity metal-on-metal injuries commonly produce intraocular foreign bodies even when the external wound appears deceptively small. Visual loss, irregular pupil, or self-sealed wounds should raise strong suspicion.<br><br>CT orbit is the preferred investigation because retained metallic fragments may later cause siderosis bulbi or endophthalmitis. A history of hammering metal on metal should always raise suspicion of an occult intraocular foreign body.<br><br>Episcleritis (A), pinguecula (D), and chalazion (B) are unrelated superficial conditions.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which clinical finding after blunt trauma most strongly suggests orbital floor fracture with muscle entrapment?","o":["Hypopyon","Lens dislocation only","Corneal opacity","Diplopia on upward gaze","Vitreous hemorrhage"],"a":3,"e":"Entrapment of the inferior rectus muscle in an orbital floor fracture classically produces restricted elevation and vertical diplopia on upward gaze.<br><br>Infraorbital nerve hypoesthesia and enophthalmos may coexist. CT orbit confirms diagnosis and helps surgical planning.<br><br>Hypopyon (A) indicates inflammation. Corneal opacity (C) and vitreous hemorrhage (E) are unrelated to orbital entrapment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops sudden painful visual loss after blunt trauma. Slit-lamp examination reveals lens opacity with rosette pattern. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Senile cataract","Snowflake cataract","Posterior polar cataract","Complicated cataract","Traumatic cataract"],"a":4,"e":"Blunt trauma may disrupt lens fibers, producing characteristic rosette-shaped traumatic cataract. Visual impairment depends on the extent and location of opacity.<br><br>Some traumatic cataracts remain stable, while others progress and require surgical extraction.<br><br>Senile cataract (A) develops gradually with aging. Posterior polar cataract (C) is congenital or developmental. Snowflake cataract (B) occurs in diabetes.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which test is classically used to detect aqueous leakage from a corneal laceration?","o":["Schirmer test","Maddox rod test","Hess chart","Amsler grid","Seidel test"],"a":4,"e":"The Seidel test uses fluorescein dye to identify aqueous humor leakage from corneal or scleral wounds. Flowing aqueous dilutes fluorescein, creating a bright green streaming appearance.<br><br>A positive Seidel test strongly suggests open globe injury requiring urgent surgical management.<br><br>Schirmer test (A) measures tear production. Hess chart (C) assesses ocular motility. Amsler grid (D) evaluates macular disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which retinal lesion is commonly seen after blunt trauma due to retinal pigment epithelial disruption?","o":["Berlin edema","Retinitis pigmentosa","Drusen","Choroidal melanoma","Cotton wool spots only"],"a":0,"e":"Berlin edema, or commotio retinae, occurs after blunt trauma and appears as transient gray-white retinal opacification due to photoreceptor and retinal pigment epithelial disruption.<br><br>Macular involvement may significantly reduce vision initially, although many patients improve over time.<br><br>Retinitis pigmentosa (B) and drusen (C) are chronic degenerative conditions. Choroidal melanoma (D) is neoplastic.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which traumatic injury is most likely to produce sympathetic ophthalmia?","o":["Corneal abrasion","Closed globe injury","Penetrating uveal injury","Episcleritis","Subconjunctival hemorrhage"],"a":2,"e":"Penetrating trauma exposing uveal tissue may trigger autoimmune bilateral granulomatous panuveitis known as sympathetic ophthalmia.<br><br>The uninjured eye may become inflamed weeks to months later due to sensitization against ocular antigens.<br><br>Corneal abrasion (A) and subconjunctival hemorrhage (E) are superficial injuries without uveal exposure.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops severe subconjunctival hemorrhage completely surrounding the limbus after trauma. What serious diagnosis should be suspected?","o":["Episcleritis","Dry eye syndrome","Acute conjunctivitis","Open globe injury","Pinguecula"],"a":3,"e":"360-degree subconjunctival hemorrhage following trauma strongly suggests occult globe rupture, especially if associated with hypotony or irregular pupil.<br><br>Careful examination without applying pressure is essential because missed globe rupture may lead to permanent visual loss.<br><br>Episcleritis (A) produces localized redness rather than circumferential hemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which structure is most commonly damaged in angle recession glaucoma?","o":["Corneal endothelium","Vitreous body","Lens capsule","Retina","Trabecular meshwork"],"a":4,"e":"Blunt trauma may split the ciliary body and damage trabecular meshwork architecture, impairing aqueous outflow and causing angle recession glaucoma.<br><br>Patients require long-term follow-up because glaucoma may develop years after injury. Gonioscopy is essential diagnostically. Angle recession damaging the ciliary body face is the classic mechanism underlying delayed post-traumatic glaucoma.<br><br>Corneal endothelium (A), retina (D), and vitreous (B) are not primary sites of angle recession.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with blunt trauma develops double vision and inability to abduct the right eye. Which cranial nerve is most likely injured?","o":["Third cranial nerve","Fourth cranial nerve","Facial nerve","Sixth cranial nerve","Optic nerve"],"a":3,"e":"Sixth cranial nerve injury weakens the lateral rectus muscle, producing esotropia and horizontal diplopia worse on gaze toward the affected side.<br><br>Blunt cranial or orbital trauma may stretch or compress the nerve along its long intracranial course.<br><br>Third nerve palsy (A) produces ptosis and exotropia. Fourth nerve palsy (B) causes vertical diplopia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ocular finding after trauma most strongly suggests lens subluxation?","o":["Conjunctival chemosis only","Corneal ulceration","Papilledema","Retinal whitening","Irregular anterior chamber depth"],"a":4,"e":"Traumatic zonular rupture may partially displace the lens, creating asymmetrical anterior chamber depth and phacodonesis.<br><br>Patients may complain of monocular diplopia and fluctuating vision. Severe dislocation may require surgery.<br><br>Papilledema (C) and retinal whitening (D) are posterior findings unrelated to lens position.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"What is the most appropriate initial management of a superficial corneal foreign body?","o":["Immediate enucleation","Intravitreal antibiotics","Pressure patch for one week","Removal under magnification","Oral steroids only"],"a":3,"e":"Superficial corneal foreign bodies should be removed carefully under slit-lamp magnification to avoid further epithelial trauma and infection.<br><br>Topical antibiotic prophylaxis is usually prescribed afterward. Metallic foreign bodies may leave residual rust rings requiring removal.<br><br>Enucleation (A) and intravitreal antibiotics (B) are unnecessary in superficial injuries.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which complication may occur if a retained iron intraocular foreign body is not removed?","o":["Pinguecula","Retinitis pigmentosa","Keratoconus","Episcleritis","Siderosis bulbi"],"a":4,"e":"Iron-containing intraocular foreign bodies may release toxic iron ions into ocular tissues, causing siderosis bulbi with retinal degeneration, iris heterochromia, cataract, and glaucoma.<br><br>Early detection and removal are therefore essential. Retained iron foreign bodies causing ocular siderosis with progressive retinal toxicity is a classic late complication.<br><br>Retinitis pigmentosa (B) and keratoconus (C) are unrelated inherited or degenerative disorders.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops severe pain, nausea, and markedly elevated intraocular pressure after blunt trauma with hyphema. What is the likely complication?","o":["Angle closure secondary to hyphema","Corneal abrasion","Retinal detachment","Optic neuritis","Chalazion"],"a":0,"e":"Large hyphema may obstruct aqueous outflow through trabecular meshwork, causing secondary glaucoma and painful pressure elevation.<br><br>Careful intraocular pressure monitoring is mandatory in traumatic hyphema management.<br><br>Corneal abrasion (B) does not usually elevate pressure markedly. Retinal detachment (C) mainly affects posterior vision.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which imaging modality is preferred for orbital fractures after blunt trauma?","o":["OCT macula","Fluorescein angiography","Schirmer test","CT scan orbit","Pachymetry"],"a":3,"e":"CT orbit provides excellent visualization of orbital walls, muscle entrapment, emphysema, and intraocular foreign bodies following trauma.<br><br>It is the standard imaging modality for orbital fracture assessment.<br><br>OCT (A) and angiography (B) evaluate retinal pathology rather than fractures.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient struck by a tennis ball complains of flashes and floaters days later. Which condition must be excluded urgently?","o":["Chalazion","Dry eye disease","Episcleritis","Pinguecula","Retinal tear"],"a":4,"e":"Flashes and floaters after blunt trauma strongly suggest vitreoretinal traction and possible retinal tear. Untreated tears may progress to retinal detachment.<br><br>Dilated peripheral retinal examination is essential urgently.<br><br>Dry eye disease (B) and episcleritis (C) do not cause photopsia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ocular trauma finding suggests traumatic optic neuropathy?","o":["Subconjunctival cyst","Mild conjunctival injection only","Corneal vascularization","Pinguecula formation","RAPD with decreased vision"],"a":4,"e":"Relative afferent pupillary defect with reduced visual acuity following trauma strongly suggests optic nerve injury.<br><br>Visual prognosis may be poor, especially with severe optic canal fractures or compression.<br><br>Conjunctival injection (B) and pinguecula (D) are unrelated surface findings.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which condition is most associated with copper intraocular foreign body retention?","o":["Retinitis pigmentosa","Siderosis bulbi","Keratoconus","Episcleritis","Chalcosis bulbi"],"a":4,"e":"Copper-containing intraocular foreign bodies may cause chalcosis bulbi, producing sunflower cataract, retinal degeneration, and ocular discoloration.<br><br>Copper toxicity varies depending on purity of retained metal.<br><br>Siderosis bulbi (B) results from iron foreign bodies.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with traumatic hyphema should generally avoid which medication?","o":["Cycloplegics","Topical antibiotics","Eye shield","Aspirin","Bed rest"],"a":3,"e":"Aspirin impairs platelet function and increases risk of secondary hemorrhage in traumatic hyphema. Rebleeding may worsen visual prognosis significantly.<br><br>Patients are usually advised bed rest, eye protection, and close monitoring.<br><br>Cycloplegics (A) are commonly beneficial for pain relief.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which traumatic injury may produce \"8-ball hyphema\"?","o":["Massive total hyphema","Corneal abrasion","Episcleritis","Retinal tear","Chalazion"],"a":0,"e":"An 8-ball hyphema refers to total dark blood filling the anterior chamber completely, usually associated with severe trauma and markedly elevated intraocular pressure.<br><br>This condition carries poor prognosis and may require surgical evacuation.<br><br>Corneal abrasion (B) and episcleritis (C) do not fill the anterior chamber with blood.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which surgical principle is most important during repair of penetrating globe injury?","o":["Delayed closure for weeks","Tonometry during surgery","Immediate keratoplasty in all cases","Routine enucleation","Watertight wound closure"],"a":4,"e":"The primary surgical goal in open globe repair is watertight closure of all ocular wounds to restore globe integrity and prevent further intraocular tissue prolapse or infection.<br><br>Additional reconstructive procedures may be staged later after stabilization.<br><br>Delayed closure (A) increases infection risk. Routine enucleation (D) is unnecessary in most salvageable eyes.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient sustains blunt ocular trauma from a cricket ball. Fundoscopy reveals a crescent-shaped retinal tear at the ora serrata. Which traumatic retinal lesion is most likely present?","o":["Lattice degeneration","Choroidal nevus","Macular hole","Dialysis retinae","Retinoschisis"],"a":3,"e":"Retinal dialysis is a circumferential retinal tear occurring at the ora serrata after blunt trauma. Young males sustaining sports-related trauma are classically affected.<br><br>The lesion may remain asymptomatic initially but can later progress to rhegmatogenous retinal detachment. Careful peripheral retinal examination is essential after blunt injury. Commotio retinae following blunt cricket-ball trauma presenting as transient retinal whitening is a classic examination scenario.<br><br>Lattice degeneration (A) is degenerative rather than traumatic. Macular hole (C) affects the posterior pole centrally. Retinoschisis (E) involves retinal splitting rather than retinal tear formation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which clinical feature most strongly suggests retrobulbar hemorrhage after orbital trauma?","o":["Mild itching","Rapid painful proptosis with reduced vision","Corneal opacity only","Chronic ptosis","Episcleritis"],"a":1,"e":"Retrobulbar hemorrhage is a vision-threatening emergency characterized by acute orbital pressure rise causing painful proptosis, tense orbit, ophthalmoplegia, and visual compromise.<br><br>Urgent lateral canthotomy and cantholysis may be required to decompress the orbit and preserve optic nerve perfusion.<br><br>Mild itching (A) and episcleritis (E) are benign surface symptoms. Chronic ptosis (D) is unrelated to acute orbital compartment syndrome.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops brownish corneal discoloration years after retained copper foreign body injury. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Siderosis bulbi","Chalcosis bulbi","Band keratopathy","Arcus senilis","Corneal dystrophy"],"a":1,"e":"Chalcosis bulbi results from chronic ocular copper deposition after retained copper-containing intraocular foreign body. Characteristic findings include sunflower cataract and golden-brown ocular discoloration.<br><br>Pure copper causes severe inflammatory reactions, whereas alloyed copper may produce slower degenerative changes.<br><br>Siderosis bulbi (A) results from iron deposition. Band keratopathy (C) involves calcium deposition in Bowman layer.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which traumatic ocular emergency classically presents with \"kissing choroidals\" on ultrasonography?","o":["Suprachoroidal hemorrhage","Retinal vein occlusion","Macular degeneration","Corneal hydrops","Papilledema"],"a":0,"e":"Suprachoroidal hemorrhage may occur after severe trauma or surgery and appears on ultrasonography as dome-shaped opposing choroidal elevations called \"kissing choroidals.\"<br><br>Patients experience sudden pain, shallowing of anterior chamber, and severe visual loss. Prognosis is often poor in massive hemorrhage.<br><br>Retinal vein occlusion (B) and papilledema (E) do not produce this ultrasonographic appearance.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child presents after pencil injury to the orbit. Which complication is particularly concerning with organic foreign bodies?","o":["Sterile fibrosis only","Retinal dystrophy","Hyperopia","Cataract alone","Severe infection"],"a":4,"e":"Organic foreign bodies such as wood or pencil fragments carry high risk of severe orbital or intraocular infection because they harbor microorganisms and incite marked inflammation.<br><br>Prompt imaging and surgical removal are often necessary. Organic material may be difficult to visualize on imaging.<br><br>Hyperopia (C) and retinal dystrophy (B) are unrelated. Cataract alone (D) is not the primary concern.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which sign is classically associated with traumatic cyclodialysis cleft?","o":["Markedly elevated intraocular pressure","Corneal edema only","Papilledema","Ocular hypotony","Lens coloboma"],"a":3,"e":"Cyclodialysis cleft occurs when the ciliary body separates from the scleral spur, creating abnormal aqueous drainage into the suprachoroidal space and causing hypotony.<br><br>Patients may develop shallow anterior chamber, hypotony maculopathy, and reduced vision. Gonioscopy confirms diagnosis. Cyclodialysis cleft causing hypotony through enhanced uveoscleral outflow is a classic post-traumatic mechanism.<br><br>Elevated pressure (A) is opposite of the typical finding. Papilledema (C) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which injury mechanism most commonly causes traumatic optic neuropathy?","o":["Penetrating corneal abrasion","Pinguecula excision","Chronic conjunctivitis","Thermal eyelid burn","Indirect blunt craniofacial trauma"],"a":4,"e":"Traumatic optic neuropathy most commonly occurs after indirect blunt craniofacial trauma transmitting force to the optic canal and nerve. Vision loss may be immediate and severe.<br><br>Relative afferent pupillary defect is an important examination finding even when fundus initially appears normal.<br><br>Corneal abrasion (A) and thermal burns (D) do not usually injure the optic nerve directly.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which traumatic retinal lesion is especially associated with shaken baby syndrome?","o":["Optic disc drusen","Drusen","Retinoschisis only in elderly","Retinal hemorrhages","Choroidal nevus"],"a":3,"e":"Extensive multilayered retinal hemorrhages are classic findings in shaken baby syndrome due to repetitive acceleration-deceleration vitreoretinal traction injury.<br><br>Associated subdural hemorrhage and encephalopathy are important systemic clues. Recognition has major medicolegal significance.<br><br>Drusen (B) and choroidal nevus (E) are unrelated degenerative lesions.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ocular trauma complication is most associated with sickle cell disease patients having hyphema?","o":["Lower risk of glaucoma","Faster hyphema clearance","Reduced rebleeding tendency","Increased risk of optic nerve damage","Corneal dystrophy"],"a":3,"e":"Patients with sickle cell disease are particularly vulnerable to optic nerve ischemia from elevated intraocular pressure in traumatic hyphema because sickled erythrocytes obstruct aqueous outflow.<br><br>Even moderately elevated pressure may threaten vision, requiring aggressive management.<br><br>These patients do not have lower glaucoma risk (A) or faster clearance (B).<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient after severe blunt trauma develops \"sunset glow\" fundus months later along with bilateral granulomatous uveitis. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Retinitis pigmentosa","Sympathetic ophthalmia","Central retinal vein occlusion","Toxic optic neuropathy","Acute retinal necrosis"],"a":1,"e":"Sympathetic ophthalmia is a bilateral granulomatous autoimmune panuveitis occurring after penetrating or severe uveal trauma. Chronic depigmentation may produce a sunset glow fundus appearance.<br><br>Prompt systemic corticosteroids and immunosuppressive therapy are essential to preserve vision in both eyes.<br><br>Retinitis pigmentosa (A) causes bone-spicule pigmentation. Acute retinal necrosis (E) is viral necrotizing retinitis rather than autoimmune trauma-related inflammation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
];